16
00:01:53,200 --> 00:01:58,200
It is bleak, it is depressing, but more than anything, it is beautifully relevant.

17
00:01:58,200 --> 00:02:05,200
A relevancy from an author who fundamentally lived what he wrote, and who understood these very conditions to his core.

18
00:02:05,200 --> 00:02:12,200
I want these core points to be accessible to all, if possible, for these ideas to work into the collective unconsciousness,

19
00:02:12,200 --> 00:02:16,200
and to help break and understand this weird matrix that we are in.

20
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:22,200
There has been numerous videos on capitalist realism, but I want this one to be the absolutely most ambitious one.

21
00:02:22,200 --> 00:02:28,200
I want it to completely encompass this book in its whole, and with an accessible form for all.

22
00:02:28,200 --> 00:02:35,200
More than anything, I want to do capitalist realism justice. This video is capitalist realism just in video form.

23
00:02:35,200 --> 00:02:52,200
After 1989, when capitalism loses its visible antagonists in the Soviet Empire, then capitalism doesn't have to defend itself as such.

24
00:02:52,200 --> 00:03:00,200
It just becomes the horizon of the imaginable. It doesn't have to be named anymore.

25
00:03:00,200 --> 00:03:03,200
It is all the more powerful because it is not named.

26
00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:07,200
Right from the start, Mark Fisher comes out swinging with the phrase,

27
00:03:07,200 --> 00:03:11,200
It's easier to imagine the end of the world than the end of capitalism.

28
00:03:11,200 --> 00:03:15,200
A phrase widely attributed to Frederick Jameson and Slavo Gizek.

29
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:22,200
As shocking as this phrase is, it's undeniably true in almost every way that capitalism isn't a mere economic system.

30
00:03:22,200 --> 00:03:27,200
It's an imposed psychological reality in condition that has permanently altered our being.

31
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:33,200
If post-mortem consciousness existed and we collectively destroyed our existence at the whims of capital,

32
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:40,200
the very idea of restricting capitalism would possibly scare more than a very real apocalyptic scenario.

33
00:03:40,200 --> 00:03:45,200
In this context, capitalism is a mere system. It is us.

34
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:50,200
This is why, when the impending threat of climate change is brought up, the reasonable response is,

35
00:03:50,200 --> 00:03:52,200
I just simply try not to think about it.

36
00:03:52,200 --> 00:03:57,200
To end capitalism is to end our contemporary human subjectivity today.

37
00:03:57,200 --> 00:04:03,200
But given the nature of this book, we must closely define what capitalism is and how it molds to us.

38
00:04:03,200 --> 00:04:06,200
Mark Fisher does just that with a whole host of prior theory.

39
00:04:06,200 --> 00:04:13,200
From the start, he elaborates on the traditional ethos of capitalism with a quote from Marx and Engels and the Communist Manifesto.

40
00:04:14,200 --> 00:04:22,200
Capital has drowned the most heavenly exceses of religious fervor, of chivalrous enthusiasm, of Philistine sentimentalism,

41
00:04:22,200 --> 00:04:25,200
and icy water of egotistical calculation.

42
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:28,200
It has resolved personal worth into an exchange value,

43
00:04:28,200 --> 00:04:35,200
and in place of the numberless, indefensible, chartered freedoms has set up that single, unconscionable freedom, free trade.

44
00:04:35,200 --> 00:04:40,200
In one word for exploitation, veiled by religious and political illusions,

45
00:04:40,200 --> 00:04:45,200
it has substituted naked, shameless, direct, brutal exploitation.

46
00:04:45,200 --> 00:04:52,200
Capitalism is the human condition that is left after culture, ritual, and symbolic elaboration is dead.

47
00:04:52,200 --> 00:04:55,200
The new culture is now consumption and spectacle.

48
00:04:55,200 --> 00:05:02,200
It moves into the aesthetic realm, and as aesthetics and rational ideation go, we see capitalism as the ultimate purveyor.

49
00:05:02,200 --> 00:05:06,200
Humans do not merely go on military conquests like Genghis Khan.

50
00:05:06,200 --> 00:05:10,200
We do not merely kill and burn down villages for fundamental power and control.

51
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:18,200
Instead, we set up camp in foreign countries and systematically set up shop and exploit human labor with the shiny facade of progress.

52
00:05:18,200 --> 00:05:24,200
But only when the exploited recognize the game they are being subjected to, they revolt and fight back.

53
00:05:24,200 --> 00:05:29,200
Then extreme brutality emerges, a brutality that is arguably worse than prior forms.

54
00:05:29,200 --> 00:05:36,200
Brutality like we saw in King Leopold II's Free State of Congo, plantation slavery in Cuba and in the Caribbean.

55
00:05:36,200 --> 00:05:42,200
Brutality doesn't cease to exist, it's simply massed, it's a more efficient and systemic endeavor.

56
00:05:42,200 --> 00:05:49,200
Capitalism sucks up culture, it sucks up history, turns the very things that often made us human into museum pieces.

57
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:52,200
Everything is objectified, it's commodified.

58
00:05:52,200 --> 00:05:58,200
With Fukuyama's idea that we have reached the apex with liberal capitalism after the fall of the Berlin Wall,

59
00:05:58,200 --> 00:06:04,200
Mark Fisher believes that critical insight into late capitalism is often Nietzschean rather than Marxist.

60
00:06:04,200 --> 00:06:08,200
Nietzsche wrote about the overflow of history into the human condition.

61
00:06:08,200 --> 00:06:14,200
We have replaced human engagement in life, culture, and politics into spectatorship.

62
00:06:14,200 --> 00:06:17,200
We retroactively learn what it is to be human.

63
00:06:17,200 --> 00:06:22,200
We retroactively examine truth rather than engage into activities that make it so.

64
00:06:22,200 --> 00:06:29,200
Fisher quotes Nietzsche's most prescient pages are those in which he describes the over-saturation of an age with history.

65
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:34,200
It leads an age into a dangerous mood of irony in regard to itself.

66
00:06:34,200 --> 00:06:40,200
He wrote in untimely meditations and subsequently into the even more dangerous mood of cynicism,

67
00:06:40,200 --> 00:06:47,200
in which cosmopolitan fingering, a detached spectatorialism, replaces engagement and involvement.

68
00:06:47,200 --> 00:06:56,200
This is the condition of Nietzsche's last man, who has seen everything but is decadently enfeebled precisely by this excess of self-awareness.

69
00:06:56,200 --> 00:06:59,200
This quote absolutely hit me to my core.

70
00:06:59,200 --> 00:07:01,200
Think about what we are doing right now.

71
00:07:01,200 --> 00:07:10,200
We are learning about something very abstract, theory-oriented, while simultaneously ignoring the very woes that we are learning about in reality.

72
00:07:10,200 --> 00:07:15,200
This learning, this education, this self-awareness simultaneously pacifies us.

73
00:07:15,200 --> 00:07:19,200
If this isn't one of the most scary insights, I have no clue what is.

74
00:07:19,200 --> 00:07:24,200
Moving on, Mark Fisher visualizes this living from history with Kurt Cobain.

75
00:07:24,200 --> 00:07:28,200
Kurt Cobain understood this new society of historical life.

76
00:07:28,200 --> 00:07:34,200
