79
00:07:50,200 --> 00:07:51,200
It's embarrassing.

80
00:07:51,200 --> 00:07:55,200
Further, even understanding this phenomenon to Cobain was a cliche.

81
00:07:55,200 --> 00:08:00,200
These anxieties he expressed further resulted in the nihilistic facade he portrayed.

82
00:08:00,200 --> 00:08:03,200
Why does it matter if I will be replaced by something greater?

83
00:08:03,200 --> 00:08:08,200
Why does it matter if I am just another spectacle, another object of desire?

84
00:08:08,200 --> 00:08:10,200
It's not fundamentally me anyway.

85
00:08:10,200 --> 00:08:15,200
This abundance of history creates a weird, new form of nihilism.

86
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:20,200
If we know the results of our action, how time will repeat itself, why do anything at all?

87
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:24,200
This is a nihilism that works perfectly within postmodern capitalism.

88
00:08:24,200 --> 00:08:26,200
This is often not a conscious nihilism either.

89
00:08:26,200 --> 00:08:36,200
The nihilism of the past, the very Nietzschean anxieties around the loss of culture, the loss of things that make us human, is child's play to this new form of nihilism today.

90
00:08:36,200 --> 00:08:39,200
And in many ways, it isn't just nihilism.

91
00:08:39,200 --> 00:08:43,200
It's a new, pernicious form of it, one that convinces you of the opposite.

92
00:08:43,200 --> 00:08:51,200
Fisher showcases this in the film WALL-E, a movie that shows an uninhabitable world from radical human consumption,

93
00:08:51,200 --> 00:08:57,200
a movie that actively decries the forms of capitalism we are subjected to and face right now.

94
00:08:57,200 --> 00:09:02,200
This movie isn't just spectacle, it invites us in to interact and participate in it.

95
00:09:02,200 --> 00:09:06,200
We gauge the world around us, how we are contributing to global disaster.

96
00:09:06,200 --> 00:09:13,200
Because of this, there is a mass outcry from right-wing observers for, quote-unquote, attacking its own audience.

97
00:09:13,200 --> 00:09:19,200
In many ways, WALL-E is a Marxian-like film, but there is one thing, there is one huge caveat at hand.

98
00:09:19,200 --> 00:09:22,200
This film ironically feeds this capitalist realism.

99
00:09:22,200 --> 00:09:27,200
The very film performs our anti-capitalist activism and education for us.

100
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:29,200
We can consume this film with impunity.

101
00:09:29,200 --> 00:09:33,200
This corporate activism does all the work for us and perfectly pacifies us.

102
00:09:33,200 --> 00:09:39,200
Pacifies the very innate threat of human destruction into an ideal that we can pervasively enjoy.

103
00:09:39,200 --> 00:09:47,200
Where in other societies, propaganda is needed to cover up oppressive acts, the exact opposite is true with contemporary capitalism.

104
00:09:47,200 --> 00:09:50,200
Capitalism is strengthened by its own critiques.

105
00:09:50,200 --> 00:09:57,200
These corporate anti-capitalist critiques ironically act as a very reinforcement and an unconscious pacifying agent.

106
00:09:58,200 --> 00:10:03,200
As reinforcement goes, Fisher brings up the mode of mental health and contemporary capitalism.

107
00:10:03,200 --> 00:10:09,200
Marrying the work of Eros and Civilization by Herbert Marcuse, link right up above if you are interested.

108
00:10:09,200 --> 00:10:13,200
We see that mental health is a radically individualistic and internal problem.

109
00:10:13,200 --> 00:10:18,200
Psychology and mental healing are purely partitioned into an interpersonal thing.

110
00:10:18,200 --> 00:10:22,200
You have a chemical imbalance, you are super stressed, etc.

111
00:10:22,200 --> 00:10:26,200
Yet we recognize that external events play a role in this regardless.

112
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:31,200
You go to therapy after a family member dies, after you are having a rough time in life,

113
00:10:31,200 --> 00:10:34,200
but the medical apparatus never touches work.

114
00:10:34,200 --> 00:10:36,200
It never touches economics.

115
00:10:36,200 --> 00:10:38,200
That is purely off limits.

116
00:10:38,200 --> 00:10:40,200
It's off limits because of capitalist realism.

117
00:10:40,200 --> 00:10:46,200
The idea that neoliberal contemporary capitalism is simply innately us.

118
00:10:46,200 --> 00:10:51,200
Therefore, it presents a depth that even psychology hasn't even been able to systematically penetrate.

119
00:10:51,200 --> 00:10:56,200
This moves us into the newer economic working conditions that affect the western subject.

120
00:10:56,200 --> 00:11:02,200
We used to live in a Fordist world, a capitalist framework that mirrored Henry Ford's production model.

121
00:11:02,200 --> 00:11:06,200
Line workers doing the same menial task over and over and over again.

122
00:11:06,200 --> 00:11:12,200
This is where traditional Marxists derive much of their ideas around alienation and the modern state of industrialized work.

123
00:11:12,200 --> 00:11:16,200
Yet today, we are living in something more pervasive and totally different.

124
00:11:16,200 --> 00:11:20,200
We are now in a very post-Fordist economic world.

125
00:11:20,200 --> 00:11:28,200
We see that in this post-Fordist world, flexibility, nomadism, and spontaneity are absolutely essential.

126
00:11:28,200 --> 00:11:32,200
You must be flexible, willing to stretch yourself to the absolute max.

127
00:11:32,200 --> 00:11:35,200
Hyper-individuality is now favorable.

128
00:11:35,200 --> 00:11:39,200
You must follow unfounded rules that are constantly made up on the spot.

129
00:11:39,200 --> 00:11:46,200
The main character of this film is in a constant state of useless menial task, sent from hyper-bureaucracy.

130
00:11:46,200 --> 00:11:52,200
The Reagan and Thatcher promises that neoliberalism, market capitalism would eliminate the very bureaucracy

131
00:11:52,200 --> 00:11:55,200
and false appearance of progress found in Stalin's Soviet Union.

132
00:11:55,200 --> 00:12:02,200
A bureaucracy that was supposedly only found in the public sector is ironically worse in today's post-modern capitalism.

133
00:12:02,200 --> 00:12:07,200
Today's capitalism has found itself in the same dilemma of ex-Soviet states,

134
00:12:07,200 --> 00:12:13,200
the pursuit of symbols and the appearance of productivity and progress, more than the actual progress itself.

135
00:12:13,200 --> 00:12:19,200
Teachers and professors are now tasked to adhering to strict curriculum where administrators will watch their lectures.

136
00:12:19,200 --> 00:12:26,200
These educators are now more concerned with fulfilling the appearance of education rather than the education itself.

137
00:12:26,200 --> 00:12:30,200
But this isn't a phenomenon found because education is within the public sector.

138
00:12:30,200 --> 00:12:36,200
This is a new phenomenon posited by neoliberal right-wing and hyper-capitalistic governments.

139
00:12:36,200 --> 00:12:44,200
A strategy that originally took place in private schools but then subsequently found its home in public schools from a neoliberal government.

140
00:12:44,200 --> 00:12:45,200
Mark Fisher quotes,

141
00:12:45,200 --> 00:12:53,200
This is in part a consequence of the inherent resistance of certain processes and services to marketization.

142
00:12:53,200 --> 00:12:59,200
The supposed marketization of education, for instance, rests on a confused and underdeveloped analogy.

143
00:12:59,200 --> 00:13:02,200
Are students the consumers of the service or its product?

144
00:13:02,200 --> 00:13:06,200
An idealized market was supposed to deliver friction-free exchanges,

145
00:13:06,200 --> 00:13:13,200
in which the desires of consumers would be met directly without the need for intervention or mediation by regulatory agencies.

146
00:13:13,200 --> 00:13:21,200
Yet the drive to assess the performance of workers and to measure forms of labor which, by their nature, are resistant to quantification,

147
00:13:21,200 --> 00:13:25,200
has inevitably required additional layers of management and bureaucracy.

148
00:13:25,200 --> 00:13:29,200
What we have is not a direct comparison of workers' performance or output,

149
00:13:29,200 --> 00:13:34,200
but a comparison between the audited representation of that performance and output.

150
00:13:34,200 --> 00:13:45,200
Inevitably, a short circuiting occurs and work becomes geared towards the generation and massaging of representations rather than to the social goals of the work itself.

151
00:13:45,200 --> 00:13:46,200
This is what capitalism is.

152
00:13:46,200 --> 00:13:51,200
It's an elastic system that adapts, that consumes our former subjectivity,

153
00:13:51,200 --> 00:13:55,200
that pacifies us into forms of entertainment and material idealism,

154
00:13:55,200 --> 00:14:00,200
evaporating the very prior subjectivity that made us human, for better or worse.

155
00:14:00,200 --> 00:14:05,200
The concept of this contemporary capitalism is one of profound ironic contradiction.

156
00:14:05,200 --> 00:14:11,200
Fisher quotes the French philosopher Alain Béryou on this very late 20th century postmodern capitalistic paradox.

157
00:14:12,200 --> 00:14:20,200
A brutal state of affairs, profoundly inegalitarian, where all existence is evaluated in terms of money alone, is presented to us as an ideal.

158
00:14:20,200 --> 00:14:27,200
To justify their conservatism, the partisans of the established order cannot really call it ideal or wonderful,

159
00:14:27,200 --> 00:14:31,200
