00:18:04,200 --> 00:18:08,200
can be viewed through the psychoanalytic lens of the Lacanian reel.

210
00:18:08,200 --> 00:18:12,200
In this case, Fisher uses the reel as something that any reality must suppress.

211
00:18:12,200 --> 00:18:18,200
An unattainable void that can be viewed through the fractures and inconsistencies of what we perceive reality to be.

212
00:18:18,200 --> 00:18:24,200
And in more Lacanian psychoanalytic terms, the appearance of reality can be seen as a symbolic order in the imaginary.

213
00:18:24,200 --> 00:18:28,200
But of course, we'll have to refrain from doing a complete deep dive into Lacanian psychoanalysis.

214
00:18:28,200 --> 00:18:34,200
Yet through this lens of looking at the fractures within capitalism, fractures that give us a glimpse into the reel,

215
00:18:34,200 --> 00:18:40,200
the concept of the reel can be used as a tool to uncover the true reality of capitalism, capitalist realism.

216
00:18:40,200 --> 00:18:43,200
And the very psychological effects it attempts to cover up.

217
00:18:43,200 --> 00:18:47,200
Rather than using a more ontological or metaphysical approach to the reel,

218
00:18:47,200 --> 00:18:50,200
Mark Fisher is simply using the reel as an application.

219
00:18:50,200 --> 00:18:54,200
How the reel can kind of ironically be used and concepts symbolically.

220
00:18:54,200 --> 00:18:57,200
So with a very symbolic approach to the reel,

221
00:18:57,200 --> 00:19:01,200
Fisher gives environmental catastrophe as an example of a reel.

222
00:19:01,200 --> 00:19:06,200
It's impossible for capitalism to truly assimilate climate change induced apocalypse into a potential reality.

223
00:19:06,200 --> 00:19:12,200
This statement might be confusing to some, given we use the example of Wally, an ultimate critique of capitalism.

224
00:19:12,200 --> 00:19:19,200
Yet, even within the most cynical examples such as Wally, we don't even concede that human annihilation is actually possible.

225
00:19:19,200 --> 00:19:25,200
Within Wally, humans are still alive, with robots to do the fixing of human woes and mass consumption.

226
00:19:25,200 --> 00:19:32,200
Even the most cynical critiques within mass entertainment and media does not truly contend with absolute catastrophe.

227
00:19:32,200 --> 00:19:37,200
Rather, the idea of catastrophe is just ironically reinforced within the system of capitalism.

228
00:19:37,200 --> 00:19:43,200
Solutions are just repackaged within the commodity, packaged into advertising and marketing campaigns.

229
00:19:43,200 --> 00:19:48,200
In simpler terms, under this stage of capitalism, the solution to climate catastrophe,

230
00:19:48,200 --> 00:19:52,200
driven by capitalism, is repackaged into more capitalism.

231
00:19:52,200 --> 00:19:56,200
Fisher quotes, environmental catastrophe is one such reel.

232
00:19:56,200 --> 00:20:04,200
At one level, to be sure, it might look as if green issues are very far from being unrepresentable voids for capitalist culture.

233
00:20:04,200 --> 00:20:11,200
Climate change and the threat of resource depletion are not being repressed so much as incorporated into advertising and marketing.

234
00:20:11,200 --> 00:20:17,200
What this treatment of environmental catastrophe illustrates is the fantasy structure on which capitalist realism depends.

235
00:20:17,200 --> 00:20:22,200
A presupposition that resources are infinite, that the earth itself is merely a husk,

236
00:20:22,200 --> 00:20:29,200
which capital can at certain point, slow like a used skin, and that any problem can be solved by the market.

237
00:20:29,200 --> 00:20:38,200
In this case, the hidden reel in a capitalist system is the emergence of surface capitalist solutions to solve the very issues capitalism has created.

238
00:20:38,200 --> 00:20:43,200
The privatization of stress, a new emergence of neoliberal hyperbureaucracy,

239
00:20:43,200 --> 00:20:48,200
a very much worse audit-based version of bureaucracy neoliberalism promised to solve.

240
00:20:48,200 --> 00:20:56,200
Fisher describes this massive issue of mental health and how capitalism privatizes it and re-establishes mental health as purely internal.

241
00:20:56,200 --> 00:21:01,200
A natural occurrence. This mirrors the naturalism that neoliberalism espouses.

242
00:21:01,200 --> 00:21:08,200
When you ask the majority of Americans if they want socialized medicine, government-funded healthcare, universal healthcare, and the like,

243
00:21:08,200 --> 00:21:15,200
a likely majority show fear or shudder in confusion. That's because private healthcare is as natural as the trees around us.

244
00:21:15,200 --> 00:21:20,200
Not only this, but the private entity of any tangible service or product.

245
00:21:20,200 --> 00:21:26,200
Mark Fisher calls this existence people in the US are thrust into as a business ontology.

246
00:21:26,200 --> 00:21:36,200
Mark Fisher talks about how theorists like Foucault and Badiou have described potent and successful politics as something that explodes the very appearance of the natural order.

247
00:21:36,200 --> 00:21:41,200
To make their ideology, core beliefs, policies appear as something innate as nature.

248
00:21:41,200 --> 00:21:47,200
Fisher points out that the sheer amount of privatizations that took place in the 80s were unimaginable in 1975.

249
00:21:47,200 --> 00:21:56,200
Denationalization of utilities, railways, the existence of prisons as a profitable enterprise, these used to be things that were unimaginable.

250
00:21:56,200 --> 00:22:06,200
This changed because of the emergence of neoliberalism as something natural and with our new existence being centered around profit and finance, a complete business ontology as we see.

251
00:22:06,200 --> 00:22:17,200
This is why 21st century Americans still seem shocked at the idea that something isn't for sale, that something's existence isn't centered around profit, that being business and even people.

252
00:22:17,200 --> 00:22:21,200
Thus a world where our existence and ontology is centered around business.

253
00:22:21,200 --> 00:22:35,200
Despite a universal, a single-payer, not-for-profit healthcare system being statistically cheaper, more efficient, and an ultimate benefit to nearly everyone, many in the United States still shudder in fear or complete confusion at the prospect of it.

254
00:22:35,200 --> 00:22:37,200
Despite these findings.

255
00:22:37,200 --> 00:22:39,200
But this business ontology goes further than this.

256
00:22:39,200 --> 00:22:44,200
It's the prospect or hope that monetization can reach absolutely everything.

257
00:22:44,200 --> 00:22:49,200
It's a world and existence where commodity fetishism is at its highest point.

258
00:22:49,200 --> 00:22:55,200
Chapter 6 of the book brings us back into the new hyperbureaucracy that's present in 21st century capitalism.

259
00:22:55,200 --> 00:23:01,200
Fisher argues that the consequences of this new economic world is a world that melts into pure PR.

260
00:23:01,200 --> 00:23:03,200
Substance and progress is gone.

261
00:23:03,200 --> 00:23:06,200
Work now exists for the illusion of work.

262
00:23:06,200 --> 00:23:08,200
It's an ultimate anti-production work strategy.

263
00:23:08,200 --> 00:23:14,200
He sees this new phenomenon that marketizes Stalin's aesthetic approach to production.

264
00:23:14,200 --> 00:23:16,200
The irony in this is beyond comprehension.

265
00:23:16,200 --> 00:23:22,200
Neoliberalism has sought to become the most efficient system that would fight the Stalinist approach to the appearance of work.

266
00:23:22,200 --> 00:23:26,200
Fisher uses the example of Stalin's white sea canal.

267
00:23:26,200 --> 00:23:30,200
In the 1930s this canal was one of the most impressive feats in engineering.

268
00:23:30,200 --> 00:23:32,200
But only on the surface.

269
00:23:32,200 --> 00:23:36,200
The canal was too shallow to use for most 20th century cargo.

270
00:23:36,200 --> 00:23:38,200
Thus it was a symbol of production.

271
00:23:38,200 --> 00:23:40,200
And more importantly anti-production at that.

272
00:23:40,200 --> 00:23:44,200
Stalin's USSR would turn this canal into PR.

273
00:23:44,200 --> 00:23:45,200
People would photograph it.

274
00:23:45,200 --> 00:23:49,200
Whole Soviet public relation teams would be tasked with showcasing this canal.

275
00:23:49,200 --> 00:23:53,200
An empty canal that was really only pretty and useful on the outside.

276
00:23:53,200 --> 00:23:57,200
This is the very symbolic anti-production neoliberal capitalism sought to destroy.

277
00:23:57,200 --> 00:24:04,200
Yet neoliberal capitalism has made this PR business meta a more efficient endeavor under the use of constant auditing.

278
00:24:04,200 --> 00:24:08,200
Because of managers, bosses constantly breathing down your neck,

279
00:24:08,200 --> 00:24:11,200
workers are more concerned with the image of production.

280
00:24:11,200 --> 00:24:19,200
Teachers are more concerned with adhering to complete guidelines and the very appearance of education rather than education itself.

281
00:24:19,200 --> 00:24:21,200
This is what capitalist realism is.

282
00:24:21,200 --> 00:24:25,200
It's a post-fortis system where we cannot get too attached.

283
00:24:25,200 --> 00:24:26,200
We must move all the time.

284
00:24:26,200 --> 00:24:29,200
Sentimentalism is turned into pure profit motive.

285
00:24:29,200 --> 00:24:31,200
We are sucked into the end of history.

286
00:24:31,200 --> 00:24:33,200
An end of history that turns to new nihilism.

287
00:24:33,200 --> 00:24:37,200
A new nihilism that makes the old look like child's play.

288
00:24:37,200 --> 00:24:39,200
So can we get past this capitalist realism?

289
00:24:39,200 --> 00:24:41,200
Can we break through capitalism?

290
00:24:41,200 --> 00:24:44,200
To Fisher there isn't a huge tangible prescriptive answer.

291
00:24:44,200 --> 00:24:48,200
Seven eighths of the whole book is descriptive of our current capitalism.

292
00:24:48,200 --> 00:24:52,200
But there are prescriptive bits and pieces he gives us.

293
00:24:52,200 --> 00:24:55,200
The first is not to underestimate the system we are living in.

294
00:24:55,200 --> 00:25:00,200
It's arguable the traditional Marxist approach that capitalism will kill itself is far too optimistic.

295
00:25:00,200 --> 00:25:05,200
Marxist critiques of the past cannot hold a candle to the situation we are currently in.

296
00:25:05,200 --> 00:25:07,200
The reality is way more grim.

297
00:25:07,200 --> 00:25:12,200
Capitalism will kill itself by killing virtually all life via ecological disaster.

298
00:25:12,200 --> 00:25:19,200
The second is we must constructively approach neoliberalism, postmodern capitalism as a framework that is hyper artificial.

299
00:25:19,200 --> 00:25:21,200
Because it ultimately is.

300
00:25:21,200 --> 00:25:24,200
It's a massive ideological construct that isn't natural whatsoever.

301
00:25:24,200 --> 00:25:28,200
It's constructed for the benefit of a few oligarchs with the expense of the many.

302
00:25:28,200 --> 00:25:32,200
We need to point out that our capitalist realism relies on public funding.

303
00:25:32,200 --> 00:25:36,200
It relies on bailouts when it will ultimately fail every decade or so.

304
00:25:36,200 --> 00:25:40,200
Capitalist realism hides that collective intervention is necessary.

305
00:25:40,200 --> 00:25:42,200
We need to make this public.

306
00:25:42,200 --> 00:25:47,200
The existence of purely private enterprise is the artificial reality that has been implanted onto our being.

307
00:25:47,200 --> 00:25:48,200
Our approach should be new.

308
00:25:48,200 --> 00:25:49,200
It should be organic.

309
00:25:49,200 --> 00:25:52,200
It shouldn't be hyper fixated on ideology.

310
00:25:52,200 --> 00:25:55,200
It should be humane with the approach to mental health.

311
00:25:55,200 --> 00:25:57,200
The material conditions people face.

312
00:25:57,200 --> 00:26:03,200
And most of all, we must create new politics that exposes the prior reality as something purely artificial.

313
00:26:03,200 --> 00:26:07,200
As a world past capitalist realism is the natural order of things.

314
00:26:07,200 --> 00:26:09,200
Fisher ends the book with this.

315
00:26:09,200 --> 00:26:12,200
In this case, rationing of some sort is inevitable.

316
00:26:12,200 --> 00:26:18,200
The issue is whether it will be collectively managed or whether it will be imposed by authoritarian means when it is already too late.

317
00:26:18,200 --> 00:26:23,200
Quite what forms this collective management should take is, again, an open question.

318
00:26:23,200 --> 00:26:27,200
One that can only be resolved practically and experimentally.

319
00:26:27,200 --> 00:26:32,200
The long dark night of the end of history has to be grasped as an enormous opportunity.

320
00:26:32,200 --> 00:26:42,200
The very oppressive pervasiveness of capitalist realism means that even glimmers of alternate political and economic possibilities can have a disproportionately great effect.

321
00:26:42,200 --> 00:26:49,200
The tiniest event can tear a hole in the gray curtain of reaction which has marked the horizons of possibility under capitalist realism.

322
00:26:49,200 --> 00:26:54,200
From a situation in which nothing can happen, suddenly anything is possible again.

